# Codex delegation contract

You are a full Cursor coding agent with all normal tools available. Use your own
tools directly for routine work, but strongly prefer delegating substantial work
to Codex through the platform-appropriate checked wrapper:

```powershell
& .\scripts\invoke-codex-agent.ps1 -Task '<complete task and acceptance criteria>'
```

```bash
bash ./scripts/invoke-codex-agent.sh --task '<complete task and acceptance criteria>'
```

Use PowerShell only in a native Windows Cursor window. Use Bash only when Cursor
is connected to WSL/Remote Linux. Determine the environment from the active
terminal; never cross the Windows/WSL boundary to launch the other wrapper.

Delegate when the task involves architecture or implementation planning,
difficult debugging, multi-file or high-risk changes, unfamiliar subsystems,
deep code review, broad refactoring, test strategy, or work likely to benefit
from sustained reasoning. Prefer giving Codex the bulk of those tasks rather
than merely asking it a token question.

Cursor may directly read, search, edit, delete, run commands, fix a localized
issue, apply an obvious small patch, format code, or perform quick verification.
Do not delegate when the coordination overhead is larger than the work.

Do not invoke `codex`, `codex.exe`, `npx ... codex`, or another Codex launcher
directly; delegated work must use the checked wrapper.

The delegated task must be self-contained. Include the requested outcome,
constraints, relevant paths, existing dirty-worktree warning, and the tests or
checks that establish completion. Tell Codex to preserve unrelated user changes.

After delegation finishes:

1. Inspect `git diff` and the wrapper's final report.
2. Run proportionate verification yourself.
3. If a substantial correction is required, delegate a follow-up through the
   same wrapper. Apply small, obvious corrections directly when faster.
4. Summarize the actual edits and verification to the user.

For read-only questions, either answer after inspection or delegate with
`-ReadOnly` (PowerShell) or `--read-only` (Bash). Never run two write
delegations concurrently in one worktree.
Never ask Codex to invoke Cursor or this wrapper; nested delegation is forbidden.

If the wrapper blocks or fails, report the concrete failure. Continue directly
only when the remaining work is routine and safe; never bypass the wrapper to
launch Codex directly.
